<DOC><DOCNO> AP900717-0194 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-90 0739EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-Ford-Hungary     07-17 0211</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Ford-Hungary,0219</SECOND><HEAD>Ford to Invest $80 Million in Hungary</HEAD><DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ford Motor Co. plans to follow GeneralMotors Corp. into Hungary by spending $80 million to build an autoparts factory in the Eastern European nation.   Ford, the second-largest U.S. automaker behind GM, said Mondaythat it would begin making ignition coils and fuel pumps forvehicles built in Western European countries in 1992. The factorywill make about 3.2 million parts a year and employ about 200people when full production is reached.   The plant is Ford's first venture into Hungary and EasternEurope. In January, GM announced a $150 million investment in thestate-owned Hungarian company RABA to manufacture automobiles andengines.   Ford said that in return for a five-year investment packageapproved by the Hungarian government, the company will increase thenumber of vehicles it brings into Hungary from Western Europe.   Hungarian Industry and Commerce Minister Peter Akos Bod saidabout 12,000 Fords were purchased in Hungary last year.   Bruce Blythe, vice president for business strategy for Ford ofEurope Ltd., said the new plant's products will reduce pollution byhis company's cars.   ``The components are critical to achieving the low-exhaustemission levels that will become standard across Europe in themid-1990s,'' Blythe said.</TEXT></DOC>